West Nile Disease Prediction

Introduction to Background

This is a Kaggle competition project from two years ago. This project aims to predict the existence of virus spread by mosquitoes around different locations in Chicago area by using data including the weather conditions, locations of longitude, latitude, the adresses of the blocks, species of mosquitoes, the trap types implemented for reducing the number of mosquitoes, and so on. The time frame of the data is from the end of May, 2007 to the end of September, 2013. The data has also included a file that described when and where were spray used to kill the mosquitoes, but only dated between 2011 and 2013 over two years, which could not match the time frame of our existing data. Thus, I will not use the spray data in order to complete this project.

Reading in the data, the missing data are converted to 0:

library(ggmap) 
## Loading required package: ggplot2
data_dir <- "../input"
wnv <- read.csv(file.path(data_dir, "train.csv"))

spray <- read.csv(file.path(data_dir, "spray.csv"))

weather <- read.csv(file.path(data_dir, "weather.csv"))
for (j in 3:ncol(weather)) {
  weather[,j] <- as.numeric(weather[,j])
  weather[is.na(weather[,j]),j] <- 0
}

mapdata <- readRDS(file.path(data_dir, "mapdata_copyright_openstreetmap_contributors.rds"))

This step is to split the data into two groups including training group and validation group, with probabilities of 0.7 and 0.3 respectively. Setting seed equal to 1 here makes sure that each time when I run this step, the data will be split into two exactly same groups.

set.seed(1)
wnv$train_id <- sample(c("train", "valid"),
                            nrow(wnv),
                            replace = TRUE,
                            prob = c(0.7, 0.3))

Since the species and trap types are presented in words, so this step here is to transform these two features into numeric values. Then each unique type is matched to its own ID in numbers.

Species_ID <- unique(wnv$Species)
wnv$Species_ID <- match(wnv$Species, Species_ID)

Trap_ID <- unique(wnv$Trap)
wnv$Trap_ID <- match(wnv$Trap, Trap_ID)

Since the weather data is given in a separate file, I used this step to combine the weather data to the main data file. There are two versions of weather data collected by two stations. I only used the data collected by station 1 because the data collected by two stations are similar and I doubt if there will be any significant difference if using data collected by both stations. The data is filtered by dates and then matched to each column into the main data file according to specific dates.

Clarification

This project requires a two-class prediction. Since the data is extremely unbalanced, with only nearly 5.25% are positive predictions, it is extremely difficult to improve the prediction accuracy because most models will just predict the existence of virus negatively and thus give predictions in 0. Therefore, I built up the models to predict continuous probabilities instead of classes, and used rmse to evaluate the accuracy of predictions.

1: Multinomial Regression

The first model I used is the multinomial regression model. This model uses several 6-degree polynomials combines, and emphasizes the interactions between certain variables like longitude and latitude, Tmax and Tmin. The rmse for validation set is around 0.22.

library(nnet)
model <- multinom(WnvPresent ~ poly(Longitude, Latitude, degree = 6) + poly(Tmax, Tmin, degree = 6) + poly(Heat, Cool, degree = 6) +poly(Sunrise, Sunset, degree = 6) + poly(PrecipTotal, degree = 6) + poly(SeaLevel, degree = 6) + poly(AvgSpeed, degree = 6),
                  data = wnv)

2: Nearest Neighbors

Since the data is very dependent on longitude and latitude, I used the nearest neighbors as the next model for prediction. This model categorizes each point, within the nearest k training points, with whatever category that is more prevalent. In this model, I have set k to different values within the range of 10 to 100. The validation rmse is in the range of 0.232 to 0.233. The validation rmse is a little bit greater than the multinomial regression model, probably because there are only two classes and the data is significantly unbalanced. From the tuning of k below, I chose k to be 50.

library(FNN)
X <- as.matrix(select(wnv, Longitude, Latitude))
X <- scale(X)
y <- wnv$WnvPresent
X_train <- X[wnv$train_id == "train",]
X_valid <- X[wnv$train_id == "valid",]
y_train <- y[wnv$train_id == "train"]
y_valid <- y[wnv$train_id == "valid"]
wnv$wnv_pred <- knn.reg(train = X_train, test = X,
                     y = y_train, k = 50)$pred
sqrt(tapply((wnv$wnv_pred - wnv$WnvPresent)^2, wnv$train_id, mean))
##     train     valid 
## 0.2171082 0.2322914

This step is used to tune k nearest neighbors in order to find an appropriate k. As we can see from the graph below, the rmse does not differ too much as k becomes larger. Thus an apporiate k would be just the point at which the rmse stop decreasing.

rmse <- rep(NA, 100)
for (k in seq_along(rmse)) {
  y_valid_pred <- knn.reg(train = X_train, y = y_train,
                          test = X_valid, k = k)$pred
  rmse[k] <- sqrt( mean((y_valid_pred - y_valid)^2) )
}
qplot(seq_along(rmse), rmse) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal()

3: Elastic Net

What we learn from the elastic net is that the number of mosquitos in one area is the most important feature for predicting the existence of virus. Then the DewPoint, Sunset and Sunrise is also important.

X <- model.matrix(~ . - 1, data = wnv[,-c(1:7,12:13, 16, 37)])
y <- wnv$WnvPresent

X_train <- X[wnv$train_id == "train",]

X_valid <- X[wnv$train_id == "valid",]
y_valid <- y[wnv$train_id == "valid"]

4: Gradient Boosted Trees

By using the gradient boosted trees model, we can see that there are more important variables being displayed. This model also captures the learned non-linearities and interactions between variables. From this model, the number of mosquitoes is again the most important, and then followed by Sunrise, Longitude, and Latitude. The validation rmse is around 0.215, by far the lowest rmse prediction.

library(xgboost)

                 max_depth = 4, eta = 0.005, nthread = 3,

5: Generalize Additive Models

I chose the variables in this model according to the importance matrix generated by the previous gradient boosted trees model. This model paid attention to the interaction between longitude and latitude, and the interaction between the maximum and minimum temperatures. Wellthis model does not beat the gradient boosted trees model!

library(gam)
## Loading required package: splines
## Loaded gam 1.14-4
model <- gam(WnvPresent ~ lo(Longitude, Latitude) + s(Sunrise) + s(NumMosquitos) + s(Trap_ID) + s(Species_ID) + s(AvgSpeed) + lo(Tmax, Tmin) + s(Tavg) + s(ResultDir) + s(DewPoint) + s(PrecipTotal),
             data = wnv,
             subset = (train_id == "train"))

6: Keras

This is the last model that I tried. This model below predicts the classes instead of the continuous probabilities. Although it is understandable to predict 0 for all the previous models if they are predicting classes, this model predicts 1 for everything in the training and validation sets. I also tried to predict the continuous probabilities, but it predicts 0 as well as negative probabilties. Therefore, the keras model does not do a good job. Wellactually it does a terrible job at predicting extremely unbalanced data(rare data).

library(keras)
## Warning: package 'keras' was built under R version 3.4.2
X_train <- X[wnv$train_id == "train",]
y_train <- to_categorical(y[wnv$train_id == "train"], num_classes = 2)
model <- keras_model_sequential()
model %>%
  layer_dense(units = 256, input_shape = ncol(X_train)) %>%
  layer_activation(activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.5) %>%

  layer_dense(units = 256) %>%
  layer_activation(activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.5) %>%

  layer_dense(units = 2) %>%
  layer_activation(activation = "softmax")
model %>% compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer = optimizer_rmsprop(lr = 0.0005),
                  metrics = c('accuracy'))

history <- model %>%
  fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 20)
plot(history)

wnv$wnv_pred <- predict(model, X)[,1]
table(wnv$wnv_pred)

##     1 
## 10506
